      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        4966,
        5018
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"filtering\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Filter returned data"
    },
    {
      "content": "The following code illustrates how to filter data by including a <ph id=\"ph1\">`Where`</ph> clause in a query.",
      "pos": [
        5020,
        5111
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It returns all items from <ph id=\"ph1\">`todoTable`</ph> whose <ph id=\"ph2\">`Complete`</ph> property is equal to <ph id=\"ph3\">`false`</ph>.",
      "pos": [
        5112,
        5196
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The <ph id=\"ph1\">`Where`</ph> function applies a row filtering predicate to the query against the table.",
      "pos": [
        5197,
        5283
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can view the URI of the request sent to the backend by using message inspection software, such as browser developer tools or <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Fiddler]</ept>.",
      "pos": [
        5494,
        5633
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "If you look at the request URI below,  notice that we are modifying the query string itself:",
      "pos": [
        5634,
        5726
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This request would normally be translated roughly into the following SQL query on the Azure side:",
      "pos": [
        5791,
        5888
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The function which is passed to the <ph id=\"ph1\">`Where`</ph> method can have an arbitrary number of conditions.",
      "pos": [
        5956,
        6050
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, the line below:",
      "pos": [
        6051,
        6079
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Would be roughly translated (for the same request shown before) as",
      "pos": [
        6310,
        6376
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        6478,
        6579
      ],
      "content": "The <ph id=\"ph1\">`where`</ph> statement above will find items with <ph id=\"ph2\">`Complete`</ph> status set to false with non-null <ph id=\"ph3\">`Text`</ph>."
    },
    {
      "content": "We also could have written that in multiple lines instead:",
      "pos": [
        6581,
        6639
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The two methods are equivalent and may be used interchangeably.",
      "pos": [
        6811,
        6874
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The former option&amp;mdash;of concatenating multiple predicates in one query&amp;mdash;is more compact and recommended.",
      "pos": [
        6876,
        6988
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The <ph id=\"ph1\">`where`</ph> clause supports operations that be translated into the OData subset.",
      "pos": [
        6990,
        7070
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This includes relational operators (==, !=, &lt;, &lt;=, &gt;, &gt;=), arithmetic operators (+, -, /, *, %), number precision (Math.Floor, Math.Ceiling), string functions (Length, Substring, Replace, IndexOf, StartsWith, EndsWith), date properties (Year, Month, Day, Hour, Minute, Second), access properties of an object, and expressions combining all of these.",
      "pos": [
        7071,
        7420
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        7426,
        7474
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"sorting\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Sort returned data"
    },
    {
      "content": "The following code illustrates how to sort data by including an <ph id=\"ph1\">`OrderBy`</ph> or <ph id=\"ph2\">`OrderByDescending`</ph> function in the query.",
      "pos": [
        7476,
        7595
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "It returns items from <ph id=\"ph1\">`todoTable`</ph> sorted ascending by the <ph id=\"ph2\">`Text`</ph> field.",
      "pos": [
        7596,
        7667
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        8120,
        8169
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"paging\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Return data in pages"
    },
    {
      "content": "By default, the backend returns only the first 50 rows.",
      "pos": [
        8171,
        8226
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can increase the number of returned rows by calling the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Take]</ept> method.",
      "pos": [
        8227,
        8301
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Use <ph id=\"ph1\">`Take`</ph> along with the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">Skip]</ept> method to request a specific \"page\" of the total dataset returned by the query.",
      "pos": [
        8302,
        8414
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following query, when executed, returns the top three items in the table.",
      "pos": [
        8415,
        8492
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following revised query skips the first three results and returns the next three after that.",
      "pos": [
        8696,
        8792
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This is effectively the second \"page\" of data, where the page size is three items.",
      "pos": [
        8793,
        8875
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        9135,
        9339
      ],
      "content": "You can also use the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><ept id=\"p1\">IncludeTotalCount]</ept> method to ensure that the query will get the total count for <ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;i&gt;</ph>all<ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/i&gt;</ph> the records that would have been returned, ignoring any take paging/limit clause specified:"
    },
    {
      "content": "This is a simplified scenario of passing hard-coded paging values to the <ph id=\"ph1\">`Take`</ph> and <ph id=\"ph2\">`Skip`</ph> methods.",
      "pos": [
        9381,
        9480
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "In a real-world app, you can use queries similar to the above with a pager control or comparable UI to let users navigate to previous and next pages.",
      "pos": [
        9481,
        9630
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">[AZURE.NOTE]</ph>To override the 50 row limit in a Mobile App backend, you must also apply the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>EnableQueryAttribute<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/system.web.http.odata.enablequeryattribute.aspx)</ept> to the public GET method and specify the paging behavior.",
      "pos": [
        9633,
        9887
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When applied to the method, the following sets the maximum returned rows to 1000:",
      "pos": [
        9888,
        9969
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        10008,
        10063
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"selecting\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Select specific columns"
    },
    {
      "content": "You can specify which set of properties to include in the results by adding a <ph id=\"ph1\">`Select`</ph> clause to your query.",
      "pos": [
        10065,
        10173
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For example, the following code shows how to select just one field and also how to select and format multiple fields:",
      "pos": [
        10174,
        10291
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "All the functions described so far are additive, so we can just keep calling them and we'll each time affect more of the query.",
      "pos": [
        10870,
        10997
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "One more example:",
      "pos": [
        10998,
        11015
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        11312,
        11362
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"lookingup\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Look up data by ID"
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        11364,
        11461
      ],
      "content": "The <ph id=\"ph1\">`LookupAsync`</ph> function can be used to look up objects from the database with a particular ID."
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        11648,
        11703
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"lookingup\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Execute untyped queries"
    },
    {
      "content": "When executing a query using an untyped table object, you must explicitly specify the OData query string, as in the following example:",
      "pos": [
        11705,
        11839
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You get back JSON values that you can use like a property bag.",
      "pos": [
        11980,
        12042
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "For more information on JToken and Json.NET, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Json.NET<ept id=\"p1\">](http://json.codeplex.com/)</ept>",
      "pos": [
        12043,
        12129
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        12133,
        12202
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"inserting\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Insert data into a Mobile App backend"
    },
    {
      "content": "All client types must contain a member named <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Id<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, which is by default a string.",
      "pos": [
        12204,
        12286
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Id<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> is required to perform CRUD operations and for offline.",
      "pos": [
        12287,
        12354
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The following code illustrates how to insert new rows into a table.",
      "pos": [
        12355,
        12422
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The parameter contains the data to be inserted as a .NET object.",
      "pos": [
        12423,
        12487
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        12533,
        12740
      ],
      "content": "If a unique custom ID value is not included in the <ph id=\"ph1\">`todoItem`</ph> passed to the <ph id=\"ph2\">`todoTable.InsertAsync`</ph> call, a value for ID is generated by the server and is set in the <ph id=\"ph3\">`todoItem`</ph> object returned to the client."
    },
    {
      "content": "To insert untyped data, you may take advantage of Json.NET as shown below.",
      "pos": [
        12742,
        12816
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Here is an example using an email address as a unique string id.",
      "pos": [
        12965,
        13029
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Working with ID values",
      "pos": [
        13227,
        13249
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Mobile Apps supports unique custom string values for the table's <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>id<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> column.",
      "pos": [
        13251,
        13330
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "This allows applications to use custom values such as email addresses or user names for the ID.",
      "pos": [
        13331,
        13426
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "String IDs provide you with the following benefits:",
      "pos": [
        13428,
        13479
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "IDs are generated without making a round-trip to the database.",
      "pos": [
        13483,
        13545
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "Records are easier to merge from different tables or databases.",
      "pos": [
        13548,
        13611
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "IDs values can integrate better with an application's logic.",
      "pos": [
        13614,
        13674
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "When a string ID value is not set on an inserted record, the Mobile App backend generates a unique value for the ID.",
      "pos": [
        13676,
        13792
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "You can use the <ph id=\"ph1\">`Guid.NewGuid()`</ph> method To generate your own ID values, either on the client or in the backend.",
      "pos": [
        13793,
        13904
      ]
    },
    {
      "pos": [
        13909,
        13976
      ],
      "content": "<ph id=\"ph1\">&lt;a name=\"modifying\"&gt;</ph><ph id=\"ph2\">&lt;/a&gt;</ph>How to: Modify data in a Mobile App backend"
    },
    {
      "content": "The following code illustrates how to update an existing instance with the same ID with new information.",
      "pos": [
        13978,
        14082
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "The parameter contains the data to be updated as a .NET object.",
      "pos": [
        14083,
        14146
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "To insert untyped data, you may take advantage of Json.NET as follows:",
      "pos": [
        14192,
        14262
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "JObject jo = new JObject();",
      "pos": [
        14268,
        14295
      ]
    },
    {
      "content": "jo.Add(\"Id\", \"37BBF396-11F0-4B39-85C8-B319C729AF6D\");",
      "pos": [
